Was in the area visiting from Virginia and I was very pleased. Friendly guys, quick service, very nice pie! Pie wasn't too thick or thin, just right and the Hawaiian was amazing. My kids and husband were surprised. This place stands by a NYC pizza!!!!

I decided to start with a plain slice of cheese ($2.50) which was merely OK. Crust is bland, pretty flavorless, and it could've used a little more sauce. Good amount of cheese of sufficient quality but not flavorful enough to makeup for the crust & sauce. Slices with toppings looked better so I'll try one another day (but those are ~$3-4 and I can't imagine them being good enough to justify that). As-is though, this place's regular slice is on par or worse than any of the 99¢/slice places around the city. But it's 2.5x the price.  Also tried the Sausage Roll which seemed like it would be similar to a calzone, it was stuffed with less sausage than hoped (which appeared to just be bland cut up bratwurst) as well as cheese, green peppers, and onions (i hate peppers and onions so that was a bummer). No sauce though, making the whole thing a dry & bland disappointment. Even like a tablespoon of sauce would have made it at least twice as good, or some sauce to dip it in. Instead it was just mostly cheesey bread.  Consider this place only as a last resort imo, but they aren't even open late so I don't see how I'd end up back here despite it being the closest pizza place to my home. Honestly, 2 stars is generous  Actually, now that I think about it, I don't even know why I gave it a second star. This was one of the most disappointing pizza experiences I've had in New York City so far.

Possibly the best veggie pizza in all of NYC. We've been enjoying this place for years and never had a bad pizza or staff experience. It's what NY pizza should be and a half cheese, half veggie is a true delight.

Such mediocre pizza. No idea how the average rating is so high.  Went a couple of times over the last few years, decided to give it one more chance today. Got a cheese pie. Cheese is bland, sauce is also bland and there's not enough of it, and the bread is really tough and leathery- have to tear it apart with your teeth.  Two stars is probably being generous. A shame because it's in such a convenient location by the Dekalb L stop. Won't be coming back, will continue to walk the extra few minutes to get a better pizza from literally anywhere else.

This is the go to convenient pizzeria that happens to be right next to the L train subway line.  Sal's is fairly decent as it's just cheap pizza.  No fancy flavors or bursts of basil, fresh mozzarella or olive oil exploding in your mouth.  No, this is just basic pizza with basic toppings.  It's consistent in flavor and cheap enough that the lack of something better doesn't bother you.
